<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-985-332  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 985 332.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  Dec 1989 v110 n6 p35(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Clean air in offices: the stakes are high.andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The office environment has replaced the factory as the center ofthe battle for clean air in the workplace.andP;  Congress, buildingassociations, furnishing manufacturers' groups and the USEnvironmental Protection Agency are questioning how high or lowthe standards should be in order to have a clean, healthy workenvironment.andP;  Reliance on recirculated air and the gradual releaseof gases by new building materials and furnishings arecontributors to indoor air pollution.andP;  Ozone produced by virtuallyall photocopiers and laser printers is increasingly becoming ahealth hazard.andP;  Exposure to ozone gas for two hours at an averageconcentration of 1.5 parts per million (ppm) can reduce lungcapacity by 20 percent.andP;  Installation of an electrostatic aircleaner into the ventilation system can solve the ozone problembetter than increased ventilation will.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT/></DOC>